<title type="html"><![CDATA[using the expansion slot for famicom sound]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1483&amp;p=12851#p12851"><![CDATA[
Maybe so. That's a matter of opinion I suppose. <br />But Lagrange Point's music was good. Not just an enhanced version of the standard NES sound but some nice FM Synthesis audio. <br />There were creative things done with the 2A03 audio, but few can argue that there aren't benifits to being able to add upgrades. The FX chip for example. But even with the Super NES's ability to add chips in the cartridge you still had games like the DK country series that didn't need them. So there are also definatly benefits to being creative with the system's normal abilities. I suppose the question is would developers tend to  ignore the system's normal abilities if they had the option to add an upgrade? I'm not sure they would. Very vew games used an enhanced sound chip on the famicom, and very few games used the FX chip (or any other upgrade chip) on the SuperNES. <br />They're pretty much novelties. Just fun for a few games, not good for all games. And it would have been fun had some games had some enhanced sound.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=493">Super-Hampster</a> — Sat May 13, 2006 8:44 pm</p><hr />
